config BR2_PACKAGE_XOW_FIRMWARE
	bool "xow-firmware (Xbox Wireless Dongle)"
	depends on BR2_PACKAGE_XONE
	default y
	help
	  Firmware for the Xbox Wireless Dongle (transport/mt76.c in the
	  xone package), fetched and extracted at BUILD TIME from Microsoft's
	  own, officially published Xbox Wireless Adapter driver package --
	  never committed to git (G6), hash-pinned at every step (the
	  downloaded .cab, and the firmware blob extracted from it).

	  This is a maintainer decision (ACCEPTED, 2026-07-13), not a
	  default this package invented: stock bundles this exact firmware
	  (docs/stock-inventory/firmware.md), so redistributing it is
	  what parity requires. The firmware is covered by Microsoft's
	  Terms of Use (https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/legal/terms-of-use),
	  not GPL -- see docs/decisions/0003-xone-firmware.md for the full
	  analysis, provenance, and the options that were weighed before
	  this was decided.

	  Installs as /lib/firmware/xow_dongle.bin (byte-identical name and
	  content to what stock ships) plus a same-content symlink under the
	  filename xone_dongle_02fe.bin, because this project's chosen xone
	  fork (dlundqvist, see package/xone/xone.mk) requests firmware by
	  that newer per-PID name, not the older shared name stock's fork
	  used -- both names must resolve to the same bytes for the driver
	  to actually find it at runtime.

	  Covers BOTH external USB dongles a MiSTer can use: the common
	  0x02fe (Xbox Wireless Adapter for Windows, "S" revision) and the
	  older 0x02e6 (original "Xbox One Wireless Adapter", model 1713).
	  These use genuinely different firmware, so 0x02e6 is fetched and
	  installed as its own distinct blob (xone_dongle_02e6.bin), not a
	  symlink -- see xow-firmware.mk. (Stock's single-file scheme covered
	  only 0x02fe; this is a deliberate improvement.) The two internal
	  laptop-soldered PIDs the driver also binds are not shipped -- they
	  cannot attach to a DE10-Nano.

comment "xow-firmware needs xone to be enabled"
	depends on !BR2_PACKAGE_XONE
